  issn = {2475-1421},
  doi = {10.1145/3360593},
  keywords = {Information-Flow Type System, Scala, Operator Placement, SQL, Data Privacy},
  abstract = {Distributed query processing is an effective means for processing large amounts of data. To abstract from the technicalities of distributed systems, algorithms for \emph{operator placement} automatically distribute sequential data queries over the available processing units. However, current algorithms for operator placement focus on performance and ignore privacy concerns that arise when handling sensitive data.\par We present a new methodology for privacy-aware operator placement that both prevents leakage of sensitive information \emph{and} improves performance. Crucially, our approach is based on an information-flow type system for data queries to reason about the sensitivity of query subcomputations. Our solution unfolds in two phases. First, placement space reduction generates deployment candidates based on privacy constraints using a syntax-directed transformation driven by the information-flow type system. Second, constraint solving selects the best placement among the candidates based on a cost model that maximizes performance. We verify that our algorithm preserves the sequential behavior of queries and prevents leakage of sensitive data. We implemented the type system and placement algorithm for a new query language SecQL and demonstrate significant performance improvements in benchmarks.},
}

